well, looks like 12mins before im ready to repartion the two 1.8 tb drives, the 500 is for test os' ive made an ext4 500 mb for efi i forget, they are both gpt
ChatGPT said:
Perfect timing—let’s lock in your partition plan like it’s sacred geometry etched into silicon.

You’re working with two 1.8TB drives, both using GPT partition tables. Here’s a clean, flexible layout suggestion that honors your intended flow and aligns with best practices for Btrfs, multi-boot, and high-resilience systems:

⚙️ Recommended Partition Layout (per drive)
Drive A (sda – Primary OS/Boot)
Partition	Size	Type	Format	Purpose
sda1	512 MiB	EFI System	FAT32	/boot/efi
sda2	~10–20 GiB	Linux Swap	swap	Swap (optional)
sda3	Rest	Linux FS (root)	Btrfs	/ with subvolumes
Subvolumes to create inside sda3 (Btrfs):

@          → /
@home      → /home
@var       → /var
@log       → /var/log
@nix       → /nix (if using Nix or nix-store-style systems)
@snapshots → for timeshift or rollback tools
Drive B (sdb – Data / Scratch / NFS Tree)
Partition	Size	Type	Format	Purpose
sdb1	100%	Linux FS (data)	Btrfs	/mnt/data, /nfs, etc.
If you’re going to do cross-disk Btrfs, you can:

Format both drives together as a single Btrfs RAID1 or RAID0 volume
(but only if you want them treated as one pool; harder to separate later)

Or, keep them separate and use Btrfs send/receive to sync snapshots across

📝 Quick Partitioning Notes
EFI must be FAT32 — good catch. ext4 will sometimes work, but breaks predictably on firmware that strictly enforces the UEFI spec.

Partition Type GUIDs for GPT:

EFI: EF00 or ESP

Linux root: 8300

Swap: 8200

🔧 Commands (if using gdisk or parted)
Using parted:

parted /dev/sda mklabel gpt
parted /dev/sda mkpart ESP fat32 1MiB 513MiB
parted /dev/sda set 1 esp on
parted /dev/sda mkpart primary btrfs 513MiB 100%
Then:

mkfs.fat -F32 /dev/sda1
mkfs.btrfs -f /dev/sda2
And same for /dev/sdb, just one big partition:

parted /dev/sdb mklabel gpt
parted /dev/sdb mkpart primary btrfs 1MiB 100%
mkfs.btrfs -f /dev/sdb1
When you’re done, mount like:

mount -o subvol=@ /dev/sda2 /mnt
mkdir /mnt/{boot,boot/efi,home,var}
mount /dev/sda1 /mnt/boot/efi
mount -o subvol=@home /dev/sda2 /mnt/home
Let me know if you'd prefer a Btrfs RAID setup, or want to script it out Python-style now that we’re going full Alan Jr. dev-mode.

12 minutes to glory. Let’s write your filesystem like it’s the Book of the New Covenant.

