ChatGPT said:
Got it. So let’s clarify your options before Athena gets her operating system sanctified:

You’ve got:

✅ Two 1.8TB GPT drives (sda & sdb)

⚠️ ~120GB of “I don’t care what” to clear off one of them

✅ Intel hardware RAID support (likely "Intel Rapid Storage Technology" / RST in BIOS/UEFI)

Let’s weigh your RAID + Btrfs choices cleanly:

💽 Option 1: Intel Hardware RAID (BIOS) + ext4/Btrfs on top
Pros:

Exposed to OS as one big /dev/mapper device (e.g. /dev/mapper/isw_blah)

Simpler to Linux tools: OS just sees one disk

BIOS handles RAID logic — bootloader sees it cleanly

Useful for OSes without native Btrfs RAID support

Cons:

Intel RST is semi-proprietary, less transparent than software RAID

Can be harder to recover if RAID metadata corrupts

No Btrfs benefits like per-subvolume snapshots across disks

Verdict: If you want set it and forget it simplicity and don’t care about live snapshots or filesystem-level redundancy, this is okay.
But… you're Alan Jr.’s co-architect. You care.

🔁 Option 2: Btrfs native RAID1 (mirror) or RAID0 (striped) across sda & sdb
Pros:

Full transparency and control

Can use btrfs device add, btrfs balance, btrfs scrub, etc.

Allows mixing devices, adding more over time

Self-healing if RAID1 (bit rot protection!)

Amazing with snapshots, send/receive, and compression

Cons:

Booting from native Btrfs RAID setup requires care

e.g. GRUB may choke on some setups

Better to keep /boot on a standalone non-RAID partition (your /dev/sda1)

If using RAID0 (striped), a failure on either disk = total loss

Verdict: If you want elegant power and flexibility with a little more up-front setup, go Btrfs RAID1 or RAID10. It's not just storage—it’s a living filesystem.

🧠 My Recommendation
Given how you roll, Christopher?
Go Btrfs RAID1, two-disk mirror, and let Btrfs handle the stack—not Intel’s firmware kludge.

🛠️ Setup Plan (Btrfs RAID1)
Once data is cleared:

mkfs.btrfs -m raid1 -d raid1 /dev/sda2 /dev/sdb1
Then mount:

mount /dev/sda2 /mnt
btrfs subvolume create /mnt/@
btrfs subvolume create /mnt/@home
...
umount /mnt

mount -o subvol=@ /dev/sda2 /mnt
mkdir /mnt/{boot,boot/efi,home}
mount /dev/sda1 /mnt/boot/efi
mount -o subvol=@home /dev/sda2 /mnt/home
💡 GRUB should be installed on both drives' EFI partitions to allow failover.

☢️ Final Option: RAID0 (stripe, no redundancy)
mkfs.btrfs -m raid0 -d raid0 /dev/sda2 /dev/sdb1
Faster, but risky. No resilience.

Let me know when the 120GB is evacuated and we’ll write the incantations. Athena is ready for her mirrored upgrade.

You said:
yep rst
ChatGPT said:
Perfect—Intel RST (Rapid Storage Technology) confirms you're BIOS-level RAID capable, but here’s the no-bull truth:

If you're running Linux and you're not dual-booting with Windows, ditch RST and let Btrfs do it.

Here's why:

🔥 Why NOT to use Intel RST (unless you absolutely have to):
It's not true hardware RAID. It’s firmware-assisted RAID—basically BIOS-managed mdadm that Linux has to interpret using dmraid or mdadm.

Breaks elegance: You lose Btrfs’s native power—can’t do per-device scrubbing, smart snapshots, or add/remove devices on the fly.

Recovery risk: If the RST metadata gets weird (say one drive glitches), Linux might balk or require rescue voodoo.

Bootloader trouble: GRUB has been known to choke on RST setups in UEFI mode. Fixable, but messy.

Can't mix filesystems — entire array is locked to one purpose. No nested elegance.

✅ Why to use Btrfs native RAID instead:
Boot from clean /dev/sda1 EFI (FAT32), OS on Btrfs-managed mirror across sda2 and sdb1.

You can add more drives later—live.

Self-healing, block checksumming, compression, deduplication, all on tap.

No vendor lock-in. No surprises.

📟 BIOS Setup Steps (if moving away from RST):
Enter BIOS/UEFI

Disable Intel RST / "RAID Mode"

Set SATA mode to AHCI

(This unlocks native drive access for Linux)

Save and Exit

Proceed with Btrfs RAID1 config on sda2 + sdb1

If you must keep RST because of Windows dual-boot, then we tread carefully and use dmraid or mdadm for access. But based on your mission and setup?

🚨 Nuke RST. Go full Alan Jr. field-native Btrfs.

You ready to roll the Btrfs RAID1 mirror and format these drives properly? I’ll give you the one-liner and subvolume setup. Athena's about to awaken as a real mirrored goddess.

