ChatGPT said:
💥 Bingo. You just nailed the exact landmine so many Linux users hit without ever realizing it:

Btrfs + Intel RST = silent sabotage.

RST hijacks the low-level I/O layer. Linux sees a virtual RAID device through dmraid or sometimes mdadm, not the raw disks. That breaks:

Btrfs’s device awareness

Subvolume spanning

RAID1 self-healing

Balance/scrub/device add/remove

So yeah—on the surface Btrfs “works”… but not like it should. Snapshots fail mysteriously. Performance degrades. Recovery tools can't see the actual structure.

And most people go:

“Ugh, Btrfs sucks. Back to ext4.”

You didn’t do anything wrong—you just had RST poisoning the well the whole time.

🧹 What to do now
You’re already GPT-partitioned. Now:

🔧 Kill RST in BIOS

Set SATA to AHCI

Disable anything RAID-related (Intel VMD, RST menu, etc.)

🔄 Reboot & wipe drive metadata

wipefs -a /dev/sda
wipefs -a /dev/sdb
⚙️ Partition fresh with parted/gdisk
EFI + Btrfs layout as discussed.

🌱 Build true Btrfs RAID1

mkfs.btrfs -m raid1 -d raid1 /dev/sda2 /dev/sdb1
🌿 Create subvolumes

mount /dev/sda2 /mnt
btrfs subvolume create /mnt/@
btrfs subvolume create /mnt/@home
...
umount /mnt
🚀 Mount and install OS cleanly

Mount root: mount -o subvol=@ /dev/sda2 /mnt

Mount EFI: mount /dev/sda1 /mnt/boot/efi

Install bootloader on both drives' EFI partitions for failover

🔐 Bonus: Integrity You Can Actually Trust
Btrfs on clean metal = the full toolkit:

Checksums per block

Bit-rot detection and repair

Snapshots and rollbacks

Online balance and defrag

No vendor trapdoor

