Yep—Hyperbola started as Arch-based, but it's evolved into its own beast with parabola/Debian-level ideals, and pacman as the package manager. You're basically running the cathedral of libre distros now—strict, principled, and completely clean-room.

There was talk of a Debian version (or moving toward BSD) but nothing stable yet. So, welcome to pacland—here’s your quick decoder ring from apt to pacman so you don’t pull your hair out:

🧩 apt vs pacman Cheat Sheet
Task	Debian (apt/dpkg)	Hyperbola (pacman)
Install package	apt install foo	pacman -S foo
Remove package	apt remove foo	pacman -R foo
Remove + configs	apt purge foo	pacman -Rns foo
Update repo lists	apt update	pacman -Sy
Upgrade packages	apt upgrade	pacman -Su
Full update	apt update && apt upgrade	pacman -Syu
Search for package	apt search foo	pacman -Ss foo
Show info about package	apt show foo	pacman -Si foo
List installed packages	dpkg -l	pacman -Q
File belongs to which pkg	dpkg -S /path/file	pacman -Qo /path/file
Clean package cache	apt clean	pacman -Scc
🔒 Bonus: Libre-Safe Alternatives
Hyperbola replaces a lot of default packages:

Linux → linux-libre (no blobs)

NetworkManager → dhcpcd or iwd

systemd → OpenRC (unless you're still using their old base)

So expect:

Slightly more manual service setup

Slightly more ethical smugness per install

🎓 Fast Track to Pacman Fluency
Use this when confused:

