ChatGPT said:
Ah, now we're talking long-game. A 500GB sacrificial disk to prepare for the coming BSD adventure? Perfect. That becomes your beachhead into the old continent—cold, beautiful, and absolutely unforgiving if you don’t pay tribute at every mount point.

🧭 The 500GB BSD Adventure Plan
🚩 Purpose:
Set aside clean, bootable space for HyperbolaBSD, FreeBSD, OpenBSD, or some future beast.

Partitioned and formatted in a way that's cross-BSD compatible.

Fully independent of the Btrfs mirrored Linux universe you're building.

🧱 Disk Partition Layout (MBR vs GPT)
BSD can boot from GPT (with UEFI), but OpenBSD and older BSDs still love MBR + BSD disklabels.

Let’s make it GPT + UEFI but BSD-friendly.

Partition	Size	Type	Format	Notes
sdc1	512 MiB	EFI System	FAT32	Shared /boot/efi if needed
sdc2	~16 GiB	Root (/)	UFS2/ZFS	Initial OS install target
sdc3	~8 GiB	Swap	swap	Standard BSD swap
sdc4	~rest	/home, /usr	UFS2/ZFS	Large storage or ports/jails
💡 BSD uses its own partitioning inside sdc2—we don’t slice it up like Linux LVM. You boot into BSD, and it carves up sdc2 into “a”, “b”, “c” partitions inside a disklabel.

🛠️ Partition Script (bash, executed from Linux)
#!/bin/bash
set -euo pipefail

DISK="/dev/sdc"

echo ">>> Wiping $DISK..."
wipefs -a "$DISK"

echo ">>> Creating GPT with BSD-friendly layout..."
parted -s "$DISK" mklabel gpt
parted -s "$DISK" mkpart ESP fat32 1MiB 513MiB
parted -s "$DISK" set 1 esp on
parted -s "$DISK" mkpart primary 513MiB 17.5GiB   # Root slice
parted -s "$DISK" mkpart primary 17.5GiB 25.5GiB  # Swap
parted -s "$DISK" mkpart primary 25.5GiB 100%     # Home/scratch

echo ">>> Formatting EFI..."
mkfs.fat -F32 "${DISK}1"

echo ">>> Marked $DISK for BSD. Ready for install media."
🐚 Install Candidate Shortlist
Distro	Pros	Warnings
FreeBSD	Most user-friendly, tons of docs, ZFS native	Takes some config but very stable
OpenBSD	Clean, simple, tight security	Spartan, UFS-only unless brave
HyperbolaBSD	Future home, your ideological match	Not yet installable, prep only
MidnightBSD	Desktop-friendly BSD spin	Less known, less hardened
🪓 Slackware / Gentoo — Been There
Slackware: Beautiful archaic. You fight it, it fights back.

Gentoo: Great if you're benchmarking compiler flags. Awful if you want your life back.

