Free ~120GB at the end of the disk

Leave the space unallocated, or prep it as a partition for later use by the mirrored pair or installer

🛠️ Step-by-step (in Linux using parted or gparted)
Option 1: CLI – parted (safe & scriptable)
Let’s assume /dev/sdc4 is the big one you're resizing.

# Check the partition layout
parted /dev/sdc print

# Shrink the last partition down (e.g., from 475GB to 355GB)
parted /dev/sdc resizepart 4 380GiB
💡 resizepart will not shrink the filesystem, just the partition container.
If it’s a formatted filesystem (e.g. ext4, UFS, etc), you must shrink the FS before shrinking the partition.

Option 2: GUI – gparted (for precise, visual resizing)
If you're live-booted into Hyperbola or Debian live USB with GUI:

Launch gparted

Select /dev/sdc

Right-click on the large partition (sdc4)

Resize/Move → drag slider to the left until ~120GB is unallocated at the end

Apply

🚨 If Filesystem Needs Shrinking
If that partition is formatted as ext4 or similar:

# First, check it:
e2fsck -f /dev/sdc4

# Shrink to 360GB or so (leave breathing room)
resize2fs /dev/sdc4 360G

# Then resize partition boundary:
parted /dev/sdc resizepart 4 380GiB
⚠️ Btrfs and ZFS must be handled differently—let me know what filesystem lives in there and I’ll tailor it.

