ChatGPT said:
💣 Boom. There it is—the silent gigabyte sponge: Nerd Fonts.

These suckers aren’t fonts, they’re font megabundles from hell:

~300MB+ per font family, with every icon and glyph crammed in

Multiply that by however many you've installed...

And Git? Oh, Git loves versioning thousands of binary .ttf files like they’re Hemingway drafts

🧟 Why Your Git Repo Is Bloated:
Nerd Fonts often have huge numbers of glyphs (icons from Font Awesome, Devicons, Octicons, etc.)

If you ever cloned a full repo like nerd-fonts, you pulled:

Over 50 font families

Dozens of variants each

Each file 1–20MB

Fonts stored as binary files, which Git tracks terribly

Even if you just copied a folder in, Git thinks you're versioning the font apocalypse.

🧹 What To Do Now:
🧼 Option 1: Git-ignore them
If they're not needed in your project:

echo '*.ttf' >> .gitignore
echo '*.otf' >> .gitignore
Then:

git rm --cached path/to/fonts/*.ttf
🎯 Option 2: Only install the font you use
From the Nerd Fonts repo:

./install.sh Hack
That only installs Hack Nerd Font, not the whole warehouse.

🧳 Option 3: Move fonts outside repo
If you’re keeping them for local use, move them to:

~/.local/share/fonts/ (user fonts)

/usr/share/fonts/ (system-wide)

Then rebuild cache:

fc-cache -fv
📦 Bonus Tip: Keep Fonts Lightweight
Install just the patched font variant you need, like:

wget https://github.com/ryanoasis/nerd-fonts/releases/latest/download/Hack.zip
unzip Hack.zip -d ~/.local/share/fonts/
fc-cache -fv
You caught it early—some people find out when their Git repo is 2GB and every push takes 15 minutes. You? You just cleaned 300+MB of bloat with one insight.

🧠 One font to glyph them all—but not in your source tree, ever again.

