🔍 Summary Table
Change	1830 Edition	Post‑1837 Edition	Effect/Meaning
Author/Translation	“By Joseph Smith, Junior, Author and Proprietor”	“Translated by Joseph Smith, Jun.”	Reflects narrative identity swap: translator, not author
Ether Clause Placement	At end of paragraph 1	Moved to start of paragraph 2	Aligns structure with content ordering (Mormon vs Ether)
Moroni’s Name	Not present	Added at end of paragraph 2 in 1840	Clarifies responsibility and provenance of plates
🧠 What Was Sacrificed?
Original Role Language (“Proprietor” → “Translator”)

Shifts Joseph Smith from owner to conduit, removing legal/possessory tone.

Textual Integrity of Paragraph Structure

Moves original wording to suit later editorial logic—not necessarily reflective of plates’ chronology.

Attribution Clarity

Floods the text with explicit authorship, strengthening Mormonic lineage + prophetic anchor.

Initial Ambiguity of Authorship

The earlier structure left room for interpretation—early readers might see Mormon as the primary recorder. Later editions cement the dominant narrative with Moroni sealed and hid the text.

