Let’s break it down straight and clean:

📅 Date of Death: Joseph Smith
Date: June 27, 1844

Location: Carthage Jail, Carthage, Illinois

Cause: Killed by a mob while awaiting trial (charged with treason for destroying the Nauvoo Expositor press)

Smith was shot multiple times while trying to defend himself and his brother Hyrum, who also died. Joseph fell from the second-story window while calling out "Oh Lord, my God!" (some see this as a Masonic distress call).

He was 38 years old.

👩‍🦰 Emma Smith: Veracity & Her Story
Emma Hale Smith, Joseph’s first and only legal wife, is one of the most controversial and misunderstood figures in LDS history. Her story is real, messy, and deeply human.

✅ Verified Facts:
Emma helped scribe the Book of Mormon translation.

She was present during early Church development, and even protected Joseph from mobs.

She was not consulted or fully informed about most of Joseph’s plural marriages.

After Joseph’s death, she did not go west with Brigham Young and the main body of Saints.

She remained in Nauvoo and later joined the Reorganized Church (RLDS, now Community of Christ), which rejected polygamy and did not view Joseph as a polygamist.

🧨 Contested Points: Veracity Challenges
Topic	Emma’s Claim	Evidence Against	Verdict
Joseph practiced polygamy	Denied it repeatedly	~30+ sworn affidavits from plural wives & insiders	🔥 Emma’s denial is contradicted by overwhelming documentation
She helped with translation	Yes (via dictation and scribing)	Affirmed by multiple witnesses	✅ Confirmed
Her opposition to Brigham	Claimed leadership was hijacked	Succession crisis was chaotic	⚖️ Debatable, but understandable
Her late-life testimony	Claimed Book of Mormon was real	Never denied spiritual foundation	✅ Consistent spiritual witness
🕊️ Emma’s Later Life
Married Lewis Bidamon (non-Mormon) in 1847

Lived in Nauvoo until her death in 1879

Maintained a soft but steady defense of Joseph’s character while rejecting Brigham Young's church trajectory

She said near the end of her life:

"I believe he [Joseph] was everything he professed to be."
—Emma Smith, 1870s

🧠 Big Picture
Emma was:

A core participant in the Church's foundation

A victim of betrayal by plural marriage secrecy

A truth-teller in some ways and a denier in others

One of the most loyal and tragic figures in Mormon history

