You said:
i like rsync ill copy if its not there correct
ChatGPT said:
Perfect. rsync is your katana. Elegant. Precise. Brutal when necessary.

Let’s set up your preferred style:

⚔️ Only Copy If It’s Not There or Incorrect
This command will:

Copy files only if they don’t exist in the destination

Or if file size / mod time differs

Preserve timestamps, permissions, and structure

rsync -av --ignore-existing /source/ /dest/
Or—if you want it to update changed files too (not just skip existing):

rsync -av /source/ /dest/
And if you want it super-safe and just want to see what would happen:

rsync -avn /source/ /dest/
🧙‍♂️ Want even smarter behavior?
Delete files from /dest/ that no longer exist in /source/:

rsync -av --delete /source/ /dest/
Copy only newer files (based on mtime):

rsync -au /source/ /dest/
Show progress on big files:

rsync -avh --progress /source/ /dest/
🧠 Add It to Muscle Memory
If you're doing this regularly, save it as a script:

#!/bin/bash
rsync -avh --progress /mnt/source/important_stuff/ /mnt/dest/backup/
Call it backup.sh, chmod it, and boom—your blade is sheathed and ready.

Let me know if you want filters, exclusions, or if you're copying across SSH—rsync becomes a damn teleport spell when you wield it right.

You said:
i hate when i forget to empty the trash before one of these copies, .... it got stuck on stuff on the dest that not on the source
ChatGPT said:
💀 The cursed Trash Trap.

You’re not alone—half the world’s storage crises are just ghosts in the .Trash-1000 or ~/.local/share/Trash gumming up the gears. And yep: rsync will copy all of it, including your digital garbage, unless you tell it not to.

Let’s clean that mess up and armor you against it happening again.

🧹 Immediate Fix: Empty Trash Before Copy
From your current user:

rm -rf ~/.local/share/Trash/*
Or if you're on a mounted volume (like /mnt/dest), clean its trash:

rm -rf /mnt/dest/.Trash-*/*
rm -rf /mnt/dest/.local/share/Trash/*
That clears the shadow junk.

🧰 Future-Proof Your rsync: Exclude Trash Folders
Add this to your rsync command:

rsync -av --exclude='.Trash-*' --exclude='.local/share/Trash' /source/ /dest/
That tells rsync:

“Yo, if it's trash—leave it to rot.”

🛡️ Want to Really Protect Yourself?
Make a wrapper script called clean_and_copy.sh:

#!/bin/bash

echo "🧹 Emptying trash..."
rm -rf ~/.local/share/Trash/* 2>/dev/null
rm -rf "$2/.Trash-*/*" 2>/dev/null
rm -rf "$2/.local/share/Trash/*" 2>/dev/null

echo "🗂️  Starting copy..."
rsync -av --exclude='.Trash-*' --exclude='.local/share/Trash' "$1" "$2"
Run like:

./clean_and_copy.sh /mnt/source/ /mnt/dest/
Now you’ll never accidentally immortalize the Trash King again.

Want to build an automatic trap to detect this before you run rsync? Or maybe trap it in a pre-commit hook for backups?

Because ain’t no priest of the field got time for hauling spiritual garbage across dimensions.

