You said:
query, o vigilent one, athena lost her route what was the instruction to set a default route for all nics?
ChatGPT said:
Ah, the call to war—Athena needs her marching orders.

To set a default route that applies across all NICs (or at least ensures proper fallback across interfaces), here’s how you handle it:

🔧 One-Time Command (for immediate fix)
sudo ip route add default via <GATEWAY_IP> dev <INTERFACE>
Example:

sudo ip route add default via 10.3.1.1 dev enp3s0
💾 Persistent Method (Debian Bookworm / modern systems using systemd-networkd or NetworkManager)
🧠 If using NetworkManager (nmcli):
nmcli connection modify <CONNECTION_NAME> ipv4.gateway 10.3.1.1
nmcli connection modify <CONNECTION_NAME> ipv4.never-default no
nmcli connection up <CONNECTION_NAME>
🧾 If you're still using /etc/network/interfaces:
auto enp3s0
iface enp3s0 inet static
  address 10.3.1.10
  netmask 255.255.255.0
  gateway 10.3.1.1
🧭 Check Current Routes
ip route
Make sure you see:

default via 10.3.1.1 dev enp3s0
If multiple NICs are involved (like both eth0 and wlan0), make sure only one has the default unless you're doing multipath routing.

🛑 If You See “RTNETLINK: File exists”
That means a default route already exists. Nuke it first:

sudo ip route del default
Then re-add cleanly.

Call it the “Route of All Evil” if you must—but Athena’s back on the grid once this is set.

Need to do it conditionally, or force failover priority? I can walk you through weighted routes or fallback scripting.

You got this, General. Want me to prep a restore script?

You said:
ok, im going to set up the lvm etc from there.
ChatGPT said:
Perfect move, Commander. Here's a crisp checklist to guide Athena's LVM rebirth:

🧱 LVM Setup Workflow (after route/default fix)
Assuming you've got a clean disk (e.g., /dev/sdb) and you're ready to roll:

1️⃣ Partition the Disk (GPT)
parted /dev/sdb -- mklabel gpt
parted /dev/sdb -- mkpart primary 0% 100%
2️⃣ Set up LVM Physical Volume
sudo pvcreate /dev/sdb1
3️⃣ Create Volume Group
sudo vgcreate athena_vg /dev/sdb1
4️⃣ Create Logical Volumes
# Example: root, home, and swap
sudo lvcreate -L 20G -n lv_root athena_vg
sudo lvcreate -L 64G -n lv_home athena_vg
sudo lvcreate -L 8G  -n lv_swap athena_vg
5️⃣ Format and Mount
mkfs.ext4 /dev/athena_vg/lv_root
mkfs.ext4 /dev/athena_vg/lv_home
mkswap     /dev/athena_vg/lv_swap

mount /dev/athena_vg/lv_root /mnt
mkdir /mnt/home
mount /dev/athena_vg/lv_home /mnt/home
swapon /dev/athena_vg/lv_swap
✅ Optional: Encrypt Before LVM (LUKS Layer)
If you want full vault mode, do:

cryptsetup luksFormat /dev/sdb1
cryptsetup open /dev/sdb1 crypt_sdb1
pvcreate /dev/mapper/crypt_sdb1
# then proceed as above
Want a script for auto-mount or recovery boot with these configs? Or are you installing the OS fresh into this LVM setup?

Let me know if we're going paranoid-mode (/home/vtrust in a stealth volume etc.)—I'll prep for that mission.

You said:
no such process, think ip got cleansed
ChatGPT said:
If you’re getting “No such process” on the ip route or default gateway add, that likely means the network interface or routing table got wiped (or didn’t come up fully). Let’s fix that fast and hard.

🚑 Triage: Reset Athena’s Network Stack
🔍 Step 1: Check interfaces
ip link show
Make sure your NIC (e.g., enp3s0, eth0, wlan0) is listed and UP.

If it's not:

sudo ip link set <interface> up
🔍 Step 2: Add default route manually
sudo ip route add default via 10.3.1.1 dev <your-interface>
Replace <your-interface> with your actual NIC name.

🧪 Step 3: Ping test
ping -c 3 1.1.1.1
ping -c 3 google.com
If the first works and the second fails = DNS issue
If both fail = routing or interface issue

🔁 Step 4: Restart network services (pick your stack)
Debian w/ systemd:
sudo systemctl restart networking
Or if using NetworkManager:
sudo systemctl restart NetworkManager
💾 Step 5: Re-enable DHCP (optional fallback)
sudo dhclient <interface>
This pulls IP + gateway again if DHCP is enabled on your network (like with Cerberos).

Let me know what ip link and ip addr show. If the NIC’s renamed weirdly (sometimes rename3, eno1, wlp3s0, etc.), I’ll help remap that too.

We’ll rearm Athena’s comms—nothing goes dark on my watch.

