You're talking about a Rocky Linux-style partition layout (à la RHEL), but with no indentured servitude to Red Hat. Let's do our own sovereign remix.

🧱 Suggested Custom LVM Layout (RHEL-ish but Better)
Assuming /dev/sdb1 is the physical volume and athena_vg is your volume group:

Mount Point	Size	Notes
/	20G	Root system files
/home	64G	User data
/var	12G	Logs, databases, websites
/tmp	4G	Temporary files
/srv	20G	Services, Docker, webroot
swap	8G	Swap space
/opt	16G	Optional software
/usr	24G	Static OS content (separate if you're old-school)
You can adjust /opt, /srv, or /usr sizes depending on role.

🔧 LVM Creation Commands (you can copy/paste this)
lvcreate -L 20G -n lv_root athena_vg
lvcreate -L 64G -n lv_home athena_vg
lvcreate -L 12G -n lv_var athena_vg
lvcreate -L 4G  -n lv_tmp athena_vg
lvcreate -L 20G -n lv_srv athena_vg
lvcreate -L 16G -n lv_opt athena_vg
lvcreate -L 24G -n lv_usr athena_vg
lvcreate -L 8G  -n lv_swap athena_vg
🧽 Format and Mount
mkfs.ext4 /dev/athena_vg/lv_root
mkfs.ext4 /dev/athena_vg/lv_home
mkfs.ext4 /dev/athena_vg/lv_var
mkfs.ext4 /dev/athena_vg/lv_tmp
mkfs.ext4 /dev/athena_vg/lv_srv
mkfs.ext4 /dev/athena_vg/lv_opt
mkfs.ext4 /dev/athena_vg/lv_usr
mkswap     /dev/athena_vg/lv_swap
Mount (in a chroot install or live system)
mount /dev/athena_vg/lv_root /mnt

mkdir -p /mnt/{home,var,tmp,srv,opt,usr}
mount /dev/athena_vg/lv_home /mnt/home
mount /dev/athena_vg/lv_var  /mnt/var
mount /dev/athena_vg/lv_tmp  /mnt/tmp
mount /dev/athena_vg/lv_srv  /mnt/srv
mount /dev/athena_vg/lv_opt  /mnt/opt
mount /dev/athena_vg/lv_usr  /mnt/usr

swapon /dev/athena_vg/lv_swap
🔐 Optional Vault Partition
You can still reserve a few gigs at the end for /home/vtrust encrypted/hidden mode. I can give you a stealth LUKS+keyfile layout if you want to make that area disappear unless actively mounted.

