In XFCE, you can access the network settings via the graphical interface or from the terminal. Here’s how to get to them:

🖱️ Graphical Method (GUI):
Click the Applications Menu (mouse icon, usually top-left).

Go to Settings ➝ Network Connections.

If you don’t see it, look for “Advanced Network Configuration”.

This opens NetworkManager’s GUI (usually nm-connection-editor).

You’ll see your Wired, Wireless, and VPN settings here.

⚠️ If it’s missing, you may need to install:

sudo apt install network-manager-gnome
🖥️ Terminal Method:
View connections:

nmcli connection show
Check device status:

nmcli device
Bring up/down devices:

nmcli device connect <device>
nmcli device disconnect <device>
Edit connection (example):

nmcli connection edit <connection-name>
🧩 Optional Add-ons:
For better integration with XFCE's panel, install:

sudo apt install xfce4-indicator-plugin
Then add "Indicator Plugin" to the panel and reboot or log out/in.

