Here are three clean ways to manage your network without relying on the missing GUI:

🛠️ METHOD 1: Use nmtui (Text UI — easiest)
If NetworkManager is running, this is friendly and gets the job done.

sudo nmtui
From here you can:

Activate a connection

Edit (set static IPs, DNS, etc.)

Create a new connection

If nmtui isn’t installed:

sudo apt install network-manager
🧨 METHOD 2: Use nmcli (CLI — powerful)
Example: Connect to Wi-Fi

nmcli device wifi list
nmcli device wifi connect "SSID_NAME" password "yourpassword"
Check device status:

nmcli device
Set static IP (example):

nmcli con mod "Wired connection 1" ipv4.addresses 192.168.1.50/24
nmcli con mod "Wired connection 1" ipv4.gateway 192.168.1.1
nmcli con mod "Wired connection 1" ipv4.dns "1.1.1.1 8.8.8.8"
nmcli con mod "Wired connection 1" ipv4.method manual
nmcli con up "Wired connection 1"
⚙️ METHOD 3: Manual via /etc/network/interfaces (legacy Debian way)
Only use this if NetworkManager is completely out or disabled.

Edit the file:

sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces
Sample static IP setup:

auto eth0
iface eth0 inet static
    address 192.168.1.50
    netmask 255.255.255.0
    gateway 192.168.1.1
    dns-nameservers 1.1.1.1 8.8.8.8
Then restart networking:

sudo systemctl restart networking
🔍 Check Who’s Managing the Network
Just to verify who’s in charge:

ps aux | grep -E 'NetworkManager|wicd|dhclient'
If NetworkManager isn’t active:

sudo systemctl enable NetworkManager --now
