You said:
we need to alias the names, wlx503eaa7caf87 and wlxe0ad4750523c
ChatGPT said:
Oh yeah—those default interface names are an eyeful. Let’s tame those beasts with persistent aliases using udev rules so they show up as something clean like wifi0 and wifi1.

🧰 Step-by-step: Alias Wi-Fi Interfaces with udev
List interfaces and MAC addresses

ip link show
Output will look like:

3: wlx503eaa7caf87: <BROADCAST,MULTICAST,UP,LOWER_UP> ...
    link/ether 50:3e:aa:7c:af:87 brd ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:ff
Make note of each MAC address and which device you want it to become (wifi0, wifi1, etc.)

Create a new udev rules file

sudo nano /etc/udev/rules.d/10-network-alias.rules
Add lines like this:

SUBSYSTEM=="net", ACTION=="add", ATTR{address}=="50:3e:aa:7c:af:87", NAME="wifi0"
SUBSYSTEM=="net", ACTION=="add", ATTR{address}=="e0:ad:47:50:52:3c", NAME="wifi1"
Replace MACs as needed. The NAME= part is your alias.

Regenerate and reload udev rules

sudo udevadm control --reload
sudo udevadm trigger
Reboot or manually reload the renamed interfaces

ip link set wlx503eaa7caf87 down
ip link set wlxe0ad4750523c down
ip link set wifi0 up
ip link set wifi1 up
From now on, you'll see wifi0 and wifi1 like civilized beings instead of random UUIDs.

Let me know if you want to map eth0, wan0, or lan1 style next!

You said:
is wifi_1acceptable more readable
ChatGPT said:
Absolutely — wifi_1 is perfectly acceptable and more readable for humans.

However, udev has naming constraints:

You can use underscores (_), letters, and numbers.

Avoid special characters (like -, ., or spaces).

Keep it short (under 15 characters is safest due to kernel interface name length limits).

✅ So this works fine:
NAME="wifi_1"
Just make sure it’s unique and doesn't conflict with another interface.

Example Rule Using wifi_1
SUBSYSTEM=="net", ACTION=="add", ATTR{address}=="e0:ad:47:50:52:3c", NAME="wifi_1"
Then run:

sudo udevadm control --reload
sudo udevadm trigger
And either:

reboot
or manually bring it up:

ip link set wifi_1 up
Let me know if you'd like me to generate the full rule file based on your current interface MACs.

